1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Today is Saturday, March 9, 2013. My name is Will Griffin and I'm a research associate with the Southern Oil History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:39,000
I am with videographer John Bishop and Albany Georgia on the campus of Albany State University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

4
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:47,000
We are here with Miss Louise Broadway who played a prominent role in the local Baker County Movement.

5
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Thank you so much for being here Miss Broadway and agreeing to share your story with the Civil Rights History Project.

6
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:02,000
You're welcome. If we could just begin by giving your full name, your date of birth and your place of birth.

7
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:14,000
I'm Louise, with in Hamborough, I was born in Baker County, Georgia, a little town known as Newton.

8
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:25,000
I was born in 1930, 86, 86 in 1930.

9
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Let's talk about your childhood growing up. My childhood, experiencing growing up, I was re-appointed. My parents were a farmer, they did not have a farm.

10
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:57,000
We did not have school buses at the time that I was growing up. We had to walk to school to church. We had schools in church. We had to walk to school in the cold every morning.

11
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Some mornings it was so very cold, you could hardly feel your feelings in your hands when you get to school but they had an old potbelly stone that they would fire up and we would gather around and get warm.

12
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:21,000
That was my childhood experience of school.

13
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Did you just think that the schools, the conditions of your schools, those were normal? Did you notice the conditions of white schools?

14
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:40,000
The children would pass us on the school bus, they would drive the school and we would have to walk the school.

15
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:54,000
Regardless of your distance, some tiering, which is 10 or 15 miles to get to the church and yet the white children on the white buses would pass by them living in the same neighborhood.

16
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:59,000
But we could not ride the bus and my childhood growing up is good.

17
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:05,000
So what about your experiences in school, your teachers? Do you remember any of your favorite teachers?

18
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:15,000
I remember my teachers, one of them was Miss Salome, and one was Miss Mary, Hawkins.

19
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:33,000
We taught in the church and inside the church, you didn't have any petitions between the class rooms. They would take about three pews, first grade, and they taught from the first through the seventh.

20
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:42,000
In the same sanctuary. And the same sanctuary, one teacher, not one for each class.

21
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:49,000
And they would have a section for the first grade, second, third, fourth, fifth, up through seventh.

22
00:03:49,000 --> 00:04:00,000
That's amazing. And you had to keep quiet. You wouldn't be disturbing the teacher while she was teaching from one class to another she had a time for each one.

23
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:11,000
You know, time for the class. And that is the way we really got a good education though. Right now I can appreciate those days.

24
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:23,000
They were hot, not having heat and having to try to be quiet and listen. But we made it.

25
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And I graduated from left to seventh grade then I went to high school. High school was down in Newton. They had a, it was two high schools. One was in the east and one was in the west for the black people.

26
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:48,000
So they had two Newton colored high schools. That's right. They had a, that's right. And which one did you attend?

27
00:04:48,000 --> 00:05:05,000
Well, I went to Newton colored high school. They did not, when I was in high school, they just added the west Baker high school after my graduating from Newton colored high school.

28
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:21,000
And what was Newton colored high school like? I mean, what's it? We had a fun neighborhood. They were had baritps, army baritps. Maybe I guess they were thrown in by the state.

29
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:34,000
And they had baritps that we would go in from class to class. And they had had one little building that they call like a, I was chapel in the homemade department.

30
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:45,000
And that's where we had chapel and homemade department in one building. And then the other baritps we had different classes the teachers had them at different times.

31
00:05:45,000 --> 00:06:00,000
So where are you two? Okay. So were you an only child? Did you? No, I'm the youngest of four. Of four? Okay. So what was your relationship like with your older brothers? Is it the white chapter you and the baby?

32
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Well, I think they spoiled me because I was the youngest. I only had one brother and two sisters. And growing up the second child, which sister, she never did want me to do anything. She every time it was time for my choice for anything. She would always like to do on five minutes because she loved me so.

33
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:41,000
And I think it kind of spoiled me when she left home. Then I had chose to do that. She had to do five minutes. It was kind of hard. But we were a lovely family and we lived in a one room country shack.

34
00:06:41,000 --> 00:07:04,000
We had a bed for mother and father, bed for the girls and one for the boys. I am one kitchen, one kitchen, no dining area. But believe it or not, we made it and had open five plays. You were burnt up in front and freeze.

35
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:13,000
But we made it through. We had a joyous childhood together under the circumstances.

36
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:21,000
So what do you remember about your parents the most besides them being hard workers? What type of lessons that they seek to steal?

37
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:31,000
My parent and still in me that we had to learn to end do with what we had.

38
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:40,000
Regardless of what somebody else had, what they could afford to give us, they learned us to appreciate that.

39
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:51,000
We had to go to Sunday school, we had to go to church, air a Sunday. And we had to put church first regardless of school activities or whatnot.

40
00:07:51,000 --> 00:08:05,000
You had to go to church before you go to school activities. And they fed us. It might have been just meeting for it. But we never went hungry.

41
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:11,000
We never went hungry. My father worked at a grist meal. You know, were they grinded meal?

42
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:12,000
Grist meal.

43
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:18,000
Yeah. That's where they would take corn and grind it up to make meal.

44
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:19,000
Okay.

45
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:25,000
And that's where my father worked. And my mother worked as a maid from house to house.

46
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:27,000
Okay. Okay.

47
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:33,000
So let's go back to high school. Would you graduate from high school in what year?

48
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:41,000
1948. 1948. And what were your plans? I mean, did you know?

49
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:47,000
Well, really, really, and truly, my plans were to go to college.

50
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:59,000
Okay. But at that time, my father, I told you that was a sharecropper and my mother worked. And they was working from 50% to $1 a day.

51
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:06,000
And at that time, nowhere in the world, you know, they could send me away and away to school.

52
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:18,000
So they just, they were not able to send me away to school. So my first job was working as a maid in the kitchen working for a dollar a day.

53
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
Okay. Who were you working for? Do you remember the family you worked for?

54
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:22,000
Me, a guy.

55
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:26,000
And what, do you remember who, what, what was the name of the family that you worked for?

56
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:29,000
Oh, the name of the family was, was Mamie McConnell.

57
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,000
Mamie McConnell.

58
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:33,000
McConnell, MC.

59
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:35,000
MC.

60
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:37,000
MC.

61
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:40,000
C-O-R-R-A-L-I-B-D.

62
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:42,000
Okay.

63
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,000
Okay. So, what, what?

64
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:49,000
Well, Mamie White. I'm sorry. No, it was. Her name was Mamie White. I'm sorry.

65
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:56,000
Her name was Mamie White, not Mamie McConnell. But you and they Mamie White. That's who I worked for.

66
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
And how was it, her treatment, their treatment of you?

67
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Yeah. They treated you well?

68
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:04,000
They were, they were, they were very nice. I had to walk.

69
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:18,000
We lived about five miles from where they lived. And I would walk here morning to clean house and fix dinner and, you know, do whatever house tools that were to do.

70
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,000
Okay.

71
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:23,000
They, they, they were very nice people.

72
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:26,000
And how long did you do this? I mean, for how long?

73
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:33,000
I worked as a, uh, made for about a year after I finished high school.

74
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:34,000
Okay.

75
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,000
And then I got married. I finished high school in 1940.

76
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,000
I got married in 1949.

77
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:42,000
Who was your husband? How did you?

78
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:44,000
My husband was a grader.

79
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,000
Broadway junior.

80
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:51,000
And how'd you meet Grady? How did you meet Grady?

81
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:53,000
How did I meet him?

82
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:04,000
Well, now, the way I met Grady, I had a cousin, or I guess the name been called Carl Broadway.

83
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:08,000
He married my cousin, one of my cousins.

84
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:13,000
And I would often go spend the weekend with this cousin.

85
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:22,000
And Grady, oldest brother was rearing him because their parents passed away early.

86
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:23,000
Okay.

87
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:27,000
And, uh, way back in the, and we were very young.

88
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:34,000
We would see one another smile about it and never thought one day we would get together.

89
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:37,000
And to be husband and wife.

90
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:41,000
Now, that's how we first thought, you know, just being around one another,

91
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:43,000
and his father would bring him the church.

92
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:45,000
And my mother would bring me the church.

93
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:47,000
We just smiled at one another.

94
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:54,000
So, in the late, parties, he moved up in the community where I live.

95
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
And that's why we, how we got back together.

96
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,000
Just old friends got back together.

97
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:05,000
And one day, he asked me to marry, and I married him.

98
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:08,000
And we had five children together.

99
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:09,000
Five children?

100
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:13,000
I was second children, two, and two.

101
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:14,000
Oh, wow.

102
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:15,000
Okay.

103
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,000
So, yeah, the house full.

104
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:18,000
And yes?

105
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:19,000
Yes.

106
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,000
We maintained.

107
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:26,000
So, talk about the racial conditions in Baker County.

108
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:30,000
When did you first start noticing or, you know, begin to...

109
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:40,000
Well, really, as a child, I noticed race so far as the wife's being able to ride the school bus.

110
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:41,000
Okay, that was the first thing.

111
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:45,000
And blacks walk in the cold, and they, you know,

112
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:49,000
patients through our spitballs or whatever, we walking from a school.

113
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:54,000
Now, I noticed that, you know, as my, in my childhood.

114
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:56,000
How did you feel about that?

115
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:00,000
Did you think that that was just the way it was, or did you feel it was unfair?

116
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
Oh, at the beginning, I knew it was unfair.

117
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,000
You know, but it wasn't a thing I could do about it.

118
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:07,000
Right.

119
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:10,000
When it didn't think I could do about it, but I knew that was unfair.

120
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:17,000
But, you know, that was the way it was then, and we had to accept it.

121
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:23,000
So, going to high school, well, they had the Newton high school.

122
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:26,000
That was the white school, the Newton color high school.

123
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:33,000
So, you know, we never crossed each other past at that time.

124
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:43,000
But then later, on down in the years, when the Civil Rights Act was passed,

125
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:49,000
and time, you know, for children, these segregated schools, I would say, like that.

126
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:50,000
Okay.

127
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:55,000
Okay, then, my family, I had merit, then, and had children of my own.

128
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:56,000
Okay.

129
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:58,000
When this got started.

130
00:13:58,000 --> 00:13:59,000
1950s.

131
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:05,000
So, at the time, my husband was working for a Jane Robert Rose as a shell cropper.

132
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:06,000
Okay.

133
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:11,000
Okay.

134
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:25,000
And we signed our first child, which was the eldest, Jesse Lee Broadway, to the all white school.

135
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:38,000
So, when Jane Robert Rose heard about, we had signed the child to go, then he told my husband that if he didn't withdraw his name,

136
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:43,000
then he was going to have to pay him everything.

137
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:45,000
He owed him before the end of the year.

138
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:49,000
You see, you got your pay at the end of the year.

139
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:52,000
So, we had to withdraw.

140
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:59,000
I was the son from the white school, you know, raised you from the white school until the end of that year.

141
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Right.

142
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:07,000
At the end of that year, my husband stopped working for this farmer.

143
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:16,000
The next year, we were able to send three children to the end of the grade school.

144
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:19,000
But it was not easy.

145
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:22,000
Yeah, do you think that was sort of a widespread intimidation tactic?

146
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,000
Yeah, it was.

147
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:29,000
One of my sons was beaten so bad that he had to be hospitalized.

148
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:30,000
At school?

149
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:31,000
I mean, at school.

150
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:34,000
They brought him home that evening.

151
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:37,000
We had to bring him up to the doctor.

152
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:41,000
And he was hit so many bruises and he had to be hospitalized.

153
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:42,000
So, what happened?

154
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:46,000
Do you know that you ever talk about what exactly transpired?

155
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:55,000
Or they just again, of the white boys just jumped on them and just beat them up, stomping them, kicking them.

156
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:00,000
And he had to be hospitalized for a few days.

157
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:03,000
They would follow our children.

158
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:07,000
At this time, you know, we were busses then.

159
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:11,000
But they would follow our children home again.

160
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:13,000
Or whites would follow our children home.

161
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:18,000
When they get off the bus, they would attack them.

162
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:21,000
And I worked in Albany.

163
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:29,000
When they attacked them at school, then I got a call at work and I was driving an old pimp.

164
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:35,000
And I was driving so fast, the speed off the chain broke, trying to get home to my children.

165
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:36,000
Right.

166
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:41,000
You know, to protect them from the group that was attacking them.

167
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:42,000
Okay.

168
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:50,000
And it was very hard for us, you know, to see your child, you didn't know whether or not they was going to make it back home alive or not.

169
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:52,000
But we know somebody had to stand up.

170
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:57,000
You know, if all of us had backed up, you know, we wouldn't have had.

171
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:00,000
We wouldn't have been far as we are today.

172
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:02,000
We're not where we should be.

173
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:06,000
But it's better than it was, you know, at that time.

174
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:07,000
Sure.

175
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:10,000
So did anything ever happen to the group of boys?

176
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:13,000
Nothing happened to the group of boys.

177
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:21,000
But they did start patrolling the campus better around the school.

178
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:30,000
They had someone outside to try and keep these kind of events from happening again.

179
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:34,000
So now you said that you were working in Albany when this happened?

180
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:41,000
I worked for a medical doctor as a doctor's system for 30 years.

181
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:50,000
And this same doctor that saturday doing the marchin in the demonstration down in Baker County,

182
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:53,000
they had what you call this bloody Saturday.

183
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:54,000
Bloody Saturday.

184
00:17:54,000 --> 00:18:04,000
And some of these civil right workers and some of the citizens that was beaten up so bad,

185
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:09,000
they brought some of them to Dr. J. L. Shirley's doing an office where I worked to be treated.

186
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:14,000
He treated several just treated them for free.

187
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:22,000
Several of the freedom writers and the citizens who was beaten by the mob on that bloody Saturday.

188
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:28,000
They carried some to Camilla and Camilla refused to take in of them.

189
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:35,000
So they had to bring them to Albany or take them to all of them or some other place other than Camilla.

190
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:38,000
And so you were there when they were bringing these people in?

191
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:41,000
Oh yes, I was working for the doctor at that time.

192
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:47,000
Sharot was one of the persons that they brought in, you know, all banged and bruised.

193
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:49,000
So did you know Sharot at that time?

194
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:57,000
Well, only by yes because I lived in Baker County and the movement was in progress at that time.

195
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:00,000
So how did you respond?

196
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:01,000
What did you think?

197
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:04,000
Oh, I just thought how cruel it was.

198
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:16,000
You know, they said they had axhounds and knives and baseball bats and guns and St. Matt's missionary about this church of where I'm a member.

199
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:25,000
This is where they had to regroup and go back to the church and they had to lie down.

200
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:33,000
One of the pews and things because they was fine shots at the mid to church on that bloody Saturday.

201
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:38,000
And a lot of the churches around Baker County were attacked because they were holding meetings.

202
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:39,000
That's right.

203
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:40,000
That's right.

204
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:42,000
That's where we had our meetings.

205
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:48,000
I was one of the secretaries of the Baker County movement.

206
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:49,000
Talk about that.

207
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:55,000
In your position as secretary, but you aren't taking notes.

208
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:56,000
What else did you do?

209
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:01,000
What type of inside information do you have that could help us understand a little more?

210
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:14,000
Well, what I would try to understand what each and every one of the citizens would get up and express themselves about certain things that happen.

211
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:25,000
I would tell you know, doing the day or the night, I would have to take notes of the happenings.

212
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:27,000
What did you do with these notes?

213
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:28,000
What happened to them?

214
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:31,000
Believe it or not, I have some of them.

215
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:36,000
I have some of them down in the library.

216
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:54,000
And at East Baker Historic Society down in Newton, right now, I was looking at some of the notes that I took where one parent was saying, one of his children got hit side to head with a stick or all this kind of stuff.

217
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:03,000
And then we would have the civil rights people that some of them come down just as I would say.

218
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:14,000
And listen to some of the complaints and all of the citizens have badly treated in order to try to make things better.

219
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:20,000
We just wanted equal opportunities.

220
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:34,000
See, we had to use the books that the whites used one year, then the next year maybe, when the books were worn and all torn.

221
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:38,000
And those are the books that we get at our schools.

222
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:41,000
And we just knew that wasn't justice.

223
00:21:41,000 --> 00:22:03,000
And all the things we wanted equal opportunities, wasn't so much to integrate, you know, but if they just only had given us a chance to have materials, the wood with our children, that they had, we think we would have had better opportunities to become better men and women and educated men and women.

224
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:10,000
And the society.

225
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:22,000
All right, so you talked about the bloody sanity and civil rights work as being brought into the doctor's office.

226
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:27,000
So I take it, the doctor wasn't one who was against what was taking place.

227
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:31,000
Did you think that he supported the movement? You say his name was doctor.

228
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:35,000
And he was the J. L. Shirley Jr.

229
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:37,000
Shirley Jr.

230
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:40,000
